<div>
  <p><b>What is ACH Direct Debit?</b> ACH Direct Debit lets customers in the United States pay for your products directly from their bank account instead of using a card. It is turned off by default; you can offer it to your customers by opting in from your checkout settings.</p>
  <h3>How to enable bank account payments:</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Go to your Gumroad dashboard</li>
    <li>Navigate to the Payment methods section on the <a href="https://gumroad.com/checkout/form">Checkout form</a> page</li>
    <li>Toggle on "Allow customers to pay by bank account (ACH Direct Debit)"</li>
    <li>Click Save changes</li>
  </ol>
  <p>The setting applies to your whole account, so it covers every product you sell. You can turn it off again from the same page at any time.</p>
  <h3>Before you opt in:</h3>
  <p>Bank account payments take about 4 business days to clear, and customers only receive their purchase once the payment settles. Card payments deliver instantly, but a customer who pays by bank account will wait several days for access to their purchase. For this reason, we don't recommend enabling it for time-sensitive products.</p>
  <p>While a customer's bank payment is settling, they can't buy the same product again. This prevents double charges, and they'll see a message that their previous payment is still processing. We email them a receipt, and they get access to the purchase, as soon as the payment completes.</p>
  <h3>Who can pay by bank account:</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Customers in the United States, since ACH Direct Debit withdraws from a US bank account</li>
    <li>When enabled, the bank account option appears alongside the other payment methods at checkout</li>
    <li>If your account processes payments through your own Stripe account, the option only appears when that Stripe account supports ACH Direct Debit payments</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Things to note:</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Bank account payments are turned off by default for all creators</li>
    <li>You receive the payment through your regular Gumroad payouts once it settles, minus standard fees</li>
    <li>Bank account payments can work well for large purchases where a customer's card limit would get in the way</li>
  </ul>
